         <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng" resp="part:argr">
 	<!--translation encoded as per EG §9.2 -->
	<p>Hail! Elapsed Śaka year 728, month of Māgha, ninth of the waxing fortnight, Hariyaṅ, Umanis, Thursday. At that time<foreign> Rakai</foreign> Patapān Pu Manuku demarcated the land of Muṇḍuan and of <foreign>Haji</foreign> Huma, given as apanage to his servant Patoran. His royal corvée will be to guard the goats … the extent of the kuramvit of the holy insignia of Patapān down to the future’s future. The name is ‘The place of guarding of the goats by the apanage holder’. And so he made a dwelling at the <foreign>vindu-vindus</foreign> of the land. That is the reason that the dwelling is called ‘Vala Vindu’. Thereupon he was given the grant that <supplied reason="subaudible">the land</supplied> may not be entered by the Er Baraṅan, and by all kinds of collectors … of buying and selling. Especially those who have <supplied reason="subaudible">a record of</supplied> good or bad deeds, may the <supplied reason="subaudible">land</supplied> not be entered <supplied reason="subaudible">by them</supplied>. Thus was the grant of <foreign>Raka</foreign> Patapān Pu Manuku to his servant Patoran, and to all who reside in Vala Vindu. If there are who disturb this grant, their reward into the future’s future is <supplied reason="subaudible">that of</supplied> the five great sins</p>
	<p>The minister of Patapān at that time was the Kayumvuṅan <supplied reason="subaudible">called</supplied> Rupyan; the Mantyasih, servant of the <foreign>Rakai </foreign>Patapān, was the one <supplied reason="subaudible">named</supplied> Palindua; the Partaya was the one <supplied reason="subaudible">named</supplied> Pagəh. All of them were given gifts of 1 <foreign>dhāraṇa</foreign> of silver, 1 <foreign>yugala</foreign> of cloth per person. For the Lupaṇḍak(s) of the Er Baraṅan: 8 <foreign>māṣas</foreign> of gold; 1 <foreign>yugala</foreign> of cloth per person. For the Wahuta Pətir and the Paṇḍakyan: 1 <foreign>dhāraṇa</foreign> of silver, 1 <foreign>yugala</foreign> of cloth per person. For the 4 <foreign>pituṅtuṅs</foreign> of the <supplied reason="subaudible">two villages</supplied>, 4 <foreign>māṣas</foreign> of silver per person. The headman of Muṇḍuan <supplied reason="subaudible">named</supplied> Bunā, the <foreign>kalima</foreign> <supplied reason="subaudible">named</supplied> Sruka, the <foreign>juru murəṅ</foreign> <supplied reason="subaudible">named</supplied> Klat, the … <supplied reason="subaudible">named</supplied> Kulinā, the <foreign>daṇḍa murəṅ</foreign> <supplied reason="subaudible">named</supplied> Andhani, the <foreign>kaṇḍaṅan lavəs</foreign> <supplied reason="subaudible">named</supplied> Tija; the <foreign>kalima</foreign> of <foreign>Haji</foreign> Huma <supplied reason="subaudible">named</supplied> Sruva, the <foreign>juru siniṅ</foreign>, <foreign>parvuvus</foreign>, the <foreign>maṇḍər paraṅ</foreign> <supplied reason="subaudible">named</supplied> Guṇī: all of them they were given gifts in silver and cloth in accordance with their efforts. Minaṅa, the scribe of <foreign>Rakai</foreign> Patapān who wrote the … copper-decree, was given 8 <foreign>māṣa</foreign> of silver, 1 <foreign>yugala</foreign> of cloth.</p>         
